         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">28/8/90 ¶  ¶ Am delighted, dear Mr Ridley, that you will spare some of your bot. treasures for my institution here. I shall have to work for many months hereafter on specimens from New Guinea, and the...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">90.08.28a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Henry Ridley</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Archives, Miscellaneous correspondence.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">28/8/90</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Am delighted, dear Mr Ridley, that you will spare some of your bot. treasures for my institution here. I shall have to work for many months hereafter on specimens from New Guinea, and then will successively lay spare-samples aside for you. </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As you will be aware, Continental Australia even in its humid tropic regions is remarkably poor in epiphytal <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name>; but you shall have specimens as far as I can part with them. It may however be some time, before I can attend to this. As President (for 1890) of the Australian Assoc. for Advancement of Science I shall soon have to go to the New Zealand meeting, to instal Sir James Hector.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Australasian Association for the Advancement of Science, 3rd congress, Christchurch, January 1891.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Mr Fitzgerald<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>i.e. Robert Fitzgerald.</p>
               </note> stands alone among Botanists in never communicating bot. specimens to anyone! We all are to depend solely for all times on his figures; exquisite doubtless they are. Thus I have not been able from examination of any specimens to ascertain, what his supposed apostasioid Orchid is. From the illustrative plate, given by him, I regard it a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Prasophyllum%20">Prasophyllum </name>of monstrous growth.</hi>
               </seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M is referring to <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Corunastylis </seg>
                     <seg style="color: #000000; font-style: italic; ">apostasioides</seg>, depicted in Fitzgerald (1875–1894), vol. 2, part 3, plate 1; see R. Fitzgerald to M, 6 February 1890.</p>
               </note>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I asked for a specimen of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">this</hi>
               </seg> at least, but none is forthcoming.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found.</p>
               </note> You will be aware from my Second Census (1889), that I distinguish <name key="Apostasiaceae%20">Apostasiaceae </name>as an order. They have no real affinity to <name key="Cypripedilon">Cypripedilon</name> or other <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M recognised the order in B89.12.03, p. 192.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
